reviews.review_text: Goodstuff!!!!!! I havent heard this in a while. This stuff was played KBOO awhile back i cant remember how long it was.

What Hiatus? If only they'd taken more time off from time to time! What a treat to hear them working out these now all too familiar jams. I heard Garcia comment in an interview recently, that their rehearsal time was rather perfunctory. This seems to dispel that notion. They were an extremely well rehearsed act. After sessions like this one, they were capable of reaching the tremendous heights we all experienced. The Music Never Stopped Jams tell it all. But there are so many great other moments too...

The Meters Are All Over These Tracks... It's obvious that the Meters album "Rejuvenation" was being played by the boys around this time. It came out in 1974 and featured the tracks "Just Kissed My Baby" and "Hey Pockey Way," both of which are riffed on in these outtakes. Funny to note as well that Jerry jammed at Club Front and did a few gigs with another New Orleans legend, James Booker, in 1976. Check out the Meters and Booker if you haven't already. New Orleans funk is the dead-on funk!

Music Never Stopped The birth of a song!  The first Dead CD I ever bought was One from the Vault, and I never looked back. For that reason these songs hold a special place in my heart.  To hear such familiar tunes in such a new way is really special.  The distorto is very cool and worth several listens.  

MNS, however, takes the cake on this reel I think, as each round it gets tighter and riffs and licks we're to hear for years to come rise to the surface.  You can tell the band all believes they're on to something really cool with the chord progression and song structure.  Exciting stuff.

Nice job getting this seed on board.  I'm reminded of old feelings and experiencing new ones as well, powerful.

studio jams The first rehearsal we have from '75 is the most enjoyable to listen to - this tape surfaced only last year, but quickly became a favorite from '75. A few tunes are already well worked-out, but this session shows the band bringing in a number of fascinating jams that would soon be dropped. The Distorto is the same one that was a bonus track on the Blues for Allah disc - but it is super cool, such a different heavy-metallish approach to the Crazy Fingers theme. (It's hard to imagine Garcia singing over this track!) And track 3, the 'bouncey jam', is a caribbean-type thing that is one of the best jams the Dead ever played, in any year....I would encourage everybody to listen to at least these two tracks! Then they go into Stronger Than Dirt for a while, and other nameless jams (the titles aren't really accurate) - track 8, for instance, is a development of the funk jam they'd played sometimes in '74, like on 6/18/74. Disc two is slow going for a while, but picks up again with a fantastic Music Never Stopped jam. This song seems to catch their fancy, so they keep playing Music Never Stopped for 45 minutes....most of the session is just jamming, but this part sounds like they've started serious rehearsal.
This is fun Worth the listen
Tico Tico ... is the hidden gem here Check out Track 9: Jerry is noodling with Tico Tico and once he has it down, Jerry, Bob, Keith and Billy play it very nicely from 6:15 to 9:00.

King Solomon's Marbles Those are King Solomon's 'jams' not Stronger than Dirt, but it don't matter, just sayin stuff. By the time I got to TLEO jam, I noticed a clear Miles Davis 'On the Corner' album type vibe. Keith's Rhodes piano playing, and the time signature feels they were playing around with highlight that. Keith shoulda vibed that way more IMO, rather, he sounds sleepy on the piano for most of his career with the band. Anyhow, this is great stuff, musically, and historically. Thanks for the upload.

-SGK

Some greatness amid the tedium Hearing the boys work through Tico Tico, and Jerry playing a bit of Nature Boy in track 9 is pure gold. Some of the odd-metered stuff is fascinating. The "Bouncy jam" is boring at first, but when the flying machine gets off the ground, it's good ol' Grateful Dead at their hypnotic best.

(Not Exctly Sure What Jungle Music Refers To People,But Anyway) The Initial Jam Is The Meters "Just Kissed My Baby". Then The Band Can Be Heard Talking About The Mrters And Some Of Their Albums And Particular Tracks. Whicl Lead To A Hey Pocky Way Type Jam.Tis Fate I Would Stop To Listen To This On Fat Tuesday 2017,Forty-Two Years To The Day. Everbody Bon Ton Roulet And Remember The Meters. ART MATTERS !!!  And George,Leo And Zig Too. Forever Grateful.

Really freaking cool Wow.  This is new to me.  I don't know how I missed it for so long, but I'm glad I did.  I'll take huge, unique  surprises like this any day.  This is some really, really cool stuff.  

More fun than a frog in a glass of milk.
Awesome How can I get a download copy?

King Solomon's Marbles / Stronger Than Dirt Both King Solomon's Marbles / Stronger than Dirt are well worth the listen.   Too bad they only played this song a handful of times.  Really nice jazzy jamming.  Highly recommended
Track 11 I think there may be a subtle reference to the mind left body jam they would do sometimes. It's the part of the track where I can see them singing, "There's a band out on the highway..."
